      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lieberman's Campaigns</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Harris L Present letter disputes Sept 9 editorial urging Sen Joseph Lieberman to withdraw candidacy for Senate in November election</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I strongly disagree with your Sept. 9 editorial ''Mr. Lieberman's Campaign Hedge,'' which recommends that Joseph I. Lieberman withdraw his candidacy for the United States Senate in the November election.</p>
        <p>If Mr. Lieberman follows your recommendation and the Gore-Lieberman ticket is defeated, then a highly respected senator will be removed from national public life.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I strongly disagree with your Sept. 9 editorial ''Mr. Lieberman's Campaign Hedge,'' which recommends that Joseph I. Lieberman withdraw his candidacy for the United States Senate in the November election.</p>
        <p>If Mr. Lieberman follows your recommendation and the Gore-Lieberman ticket is defeated, then a highly respected senator will be removed from national public life.</p>
        <p>It is more important for the American people to retain the probability that Mr. Lieberman will remain on the national scene than to invite possible ''harm'' from the appointment of a Republican to the Senate by the Republican governor of Connecticut if Mr. Lieberman wins both elections.</p>
        <p>In 1960, Lyndon B. Johnson, in accordance with Texas law, ran for vice president and senator at the same time. Mr. Lieberman should take advantage of Connecticut law and do the same.</p>
        <p>HARRIS L. PRESENT  New York, Sept. 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
